<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="215" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1375,1614]" pageId="2" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,243,1375,1397]" pageId="2" pageNumber="215">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Srisanga &amp; Watthana" authorityYear="2021" box="[267,449,1376,1397]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Capparaceae" genus="Maerua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="215" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="koratensis">
<emphasis box="[267,449,1376,1397]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="215">Maerua koratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="subsp. juncea" box="[577,813,1376,1398]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Capparaceae" genus="Maerua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="215" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="juncea" subSpecies="juncea">
<emphasis box="[577,674,1376,1397]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="215">M. juncea</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[749,813,1376,1397]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="215">juncea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having petaliferous flowers with distinct 4-lobed laciniate disc and the same number of stamens, but it differs in the following combination of traits: subshrub with ascending shoots, ± 
<quantity box="[1359,1414,1412,1434]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="215" unit="m" value="1.5">1.5 m</quantity>
tall (vs. small shrub over 
<quantity box="[399,436,1448,1469]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="215" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
or climber up to 
<quantity box="[604,653,1448,1470]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="215" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
tall), reddish-brown branches with white lenticels (vs. green and striate branches), simple leaves, not glaucous beneath (vs. simple or 3-foliolate leaves, often rather glaucous beneath), and narrowly cylindrical, torulose to moniliform fruit with faintly colliculate surface (vs. ellipsoidal fruit with smooth surface).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
